				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Thanks for your replies. 
<br />

<br />
First. Not to confuse it.. I meant Lightmap압 and Radiosity. Traditional Q3
<br />
Lightmaps can be seen as the first lightbounce.. and the later added radiosity were secondary bounces where the bouncerate could be set as
<br />
compile option.
<br />

<br />
I have red the ambient light tutorial... it압 great...
<br />
but it only fakes radiosity the way a traditional global ambient light works...
<br />
so no shadow gradients in corners that would be produced be radiosity. 
<br />
I also took a look at the inbuild "editor".. (i think it압 gtkradiant ?)
<br />
and there are a lot less compile presets than in quake 3 where you had 
<br />
options for number off light bounces (from radiosity) in later gtkradiant builds
<br />
(i think it used q3map2 to compile in later versions)
<br />
To me it looks like the whole Lightmap/Radiosity things are not included in the engine anymore !!
<br />
Also from searching the net.. I have found several discussions that let me come to the conclussion that Lightmaps/Radiosity are no part of the engine anymore. 
<br />

<br />
Well the whole 3D world is more than happy that Radiosity/Global Illumination exists. Before that time you had to set dozens off dummy light sources to get a realistic ambient effect. Quake was the first game I remember that had this fantastic lighmap calculation at a time where not 
<br />
even 3dsmax had something similar included.
<br />
... and in their 4th version (maybe allready with the Doom engine) they droped it ?!.. 
<br />
I just don앖 want to believe this !!! (but I probabely have to)
<br />
No wonder that everything looks way to dark ! .. well I앖hink making 
<br />
a dark level is one thing.. but making shadow 100% black is an absolute 
<br />
"faux pas" in the 3d world !!!
<br />
Other engines are allready experimenting with realtime Radiosity/Gi
<br />
and the quake engine even skipped it압 really great pre calculated option..
<br />

<br />
Well maybe first I should do some more tests by myself how the new lighting engine
<br />
works.. before I start crying. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="Smile" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
Thank You !</span><span class=sign></span><span class="gensmall"></span>
